00:07:02.300 --> 00:07:03.255
remember where it was.

00:07:03.255 --> 00:07:05.537
PENG YING: That's for those,
like, hazy bar nights, right?

00:07:05.537 --> 00:07:06.670
You're like, oh, man--

00:07:06.670 --> 00:07:07.460
ROBIN DUA: Exactly.

00:07:07.460 --> 00:07:08.260
PENG YING: --where was I?

00:07:08.260 --> 00:07:10.080
ROBIN DUA: For those bar nights
where you had a great

00:07:10.080 --> 00:07:12.540
time and you want to figure out
where it was and you don't

00:07:12.540 --> 00:07:15.040
really remember, you could go
into Google Wallet and see a

00:07:15.040 --> 00:07:15.460
little map.

00:07:15.460 --> 00:07:17.600
And it'll tell you how
to get there, so.

00:07:17.600 --> 00:07:20.710
So those are some of the core
features of the Wallet

00:07:20.710 --> 00:07:22.240
application.

00:07:22.240 --> 00:07:26.510
So key things to highlight that
we did as part of the

00:07:26.510 --> 00:07:28.650
August release-- one is
we now support all

00:07:28.650 --> 00:07:29.430
cards in the Wallet.

00:07:29.430 --> 00:07:29.940
PENG YING: Awesome.

00:07:29.940 --> 00:07:32.950
ROBIN DUA: Two, we actually
enabled some additional

00:07:32.950 --> 00:07:34.460
security features for users.

00:07:34.460 --> 00:07:36.730
So users can now go online.

00:07:36.730 --> 00:07:38.750
In the event that they lose
their phone, they could

00:07:38.750 --> 00:07:43.460
actually disable Google Wallet
on their phone remotely.

00:07:43.460 --> 00:07:46.870
And what this web-based feature
does is it also wipes

00:07:46.870 --> 00:07:50.520
out any information that's
stored on your phone related

00:07:50.520 --> 00:07:51.840
to your Wallet.

00:07:51.840 --> 00:07:54.940
So there's added peace of
mind there for users.

00:07:54.940 --> 00:07:57.730
And the third thing that we've
done is we've enhanced the

00:07:57.730 --> 00:08:01.770
user interface to make it a
lot more user friendly.

00:08:01.770 --> 00:08:05.870
And you could see that just
adding cards to the Wallet

00:08:05.870 --> 00:08:08.220
could be done with just
a few clicks.

00:08:08.220 --> 00:08:10.880
And we're really excited
about that.

00:08:10.880 --> 00:08:11.330
PENG YING: OK.

00:08:11.330 --> 00:08:12.610
That's pretty awesome.

00:08:12.610 --> 00:08:15.970
So you previously talked about
the growth that we've

00:08:15.970 --> 00:08:18.730
currently experienced and then
where we are right now.

00:08:18.730 --> 00:08:22.100
But I guess everybody is
interested in where we go in

00:08:22.100 --> 00:08:22.630
the future.

00:08:22.630 --> 00:08:26.180
What are we doing to try to
drive growth, both in terms of

00:08:26.180 --> 00:08:28.990
number of users of Wallet and
the number of merchants who

00:08:28.990 --> 00:08:30.170
support Wallet?

00:08:30.170 --> 00:08:30.450
ROBIN DUA: Right.

00:08:30.450 --> 00:08:34.320
Well, the vision behind Wallet
is we want it to be an

00:08:34.320 --> 00:08:37.350
electronic wallet that holds
all your payment cards,

00:08:37.350 --> 00:08:40.190
loyalty cards, gift cards, but
also other types of digital

00:08:40.190 --> 00:08:43.510
objects, things that you have in
your physical wallet today.

00:08:43.510 --> 00:08:48.550
So things like identification,
as an example, or the transit

00:08:48.550 --> 00:08:56.160
pass that you use every day,
also boarding passes, and

00:08:56.160 --> 00:08:58.440
other forms of loyalty,
and so forth.

00:08:58.440 --> 00:09:01.490
So what we're trying to do is
electronify all of these

00:09:01.490 --> 00:09:04.630
things and make them easily
accessible through the phone,

00:09:04.630 --> 00:09:08.380
but also available for online
purchases and interactions

00:09:08.380 --> 00:09:10.680
online as well.

00:09:10.680 --> 00:09:15.320
In terms of distribution, as I
mentioned earlier, we have six

00:09:15.320 --> 00:09:17.890
devices that we support today.

00:09:17.890 --> 00:09:20.450
We think NFC is going to become
a standard feature of

00:09:20.450 --> 00:09:22.450
all smartphones over the
next little while.

00:09:22.450 --> 00:09:24.530
And we're already starting
to see evidence

00:09:24.530 --> 00:09:25.920
of that in the market.

00:09:25.920 --> 00:09:30.180
And as a result of that, we
want Google Wallet to be

00:09:30.180 --> 00:09:33.270
available on all devices
and all platforms.

00:09:33.270 --> 00:09:35.320
And we want it to be the
preferred way that consumers

00:09:35.320 --> 00:09:37.260
pay for things.

00:09:37.260 --> 00:09:38.090
PENG YING: So what
about merchants?

00:09:38.090 --> 00:09:39.920
How are we driving merchant
adoption?

00:09:39.920 --> 00:09:42.070
Is it just because we're driving
user adoption and

00:09:42.070 --> 00:09:44.220
merchants are like, uh-oh, OK,
there's more users so I should

00:09:44.220 --> 00:09:45.160
just support it as well?

00:09:45.160 --> 00:09:47.890
Or are we helping them
with point of sale or

00:09:47.890 --> 00:09:48.880
anything like that?

00:09:48.880 --> 00:09:50.060
Can you even get into
that at all?

00:09:50.060 --> 00:09:50.310
ROBIN DUA: Yeah.

00:09:50.310 --> 00:09:50.510
No.

00:09:50.510 --> 00:09:51.320
Absolutely.

00:09:51.320 --> 00:09:54.420
So one of the things that we've
done is we've actually

00:09:54.420 --> 00:09:59.800
created single-tap, which allows
merchants to integrate

00:09:59.800 --> 00:10:03.670
our technology into their
point-of-sale system to enable

00:10:03.670 --> 00:10:06.490
this great one-tap user
experience that combines

00:10:06.490 --> 00:10:11.240
offers, payments, loyalty into
a single interaction.

00:10:11.240 --> 00:10:13.570
One of the things that we're
trying to do is actually

00:10:13.570 --> 00:10:17.280
enable more cloud-based services
for retailers.

00:10:17.280 --> 00:10:22.190
So things like being able to
enable delivery of coupons as

00:10:22.190 --> 00:10:24.760
well as loyalty information
from the cloud back to the

00:10:24.760 --> 00:10:25.880
point of sale.

00:10:25.880 --> 00:10:31.920
And we're also enabling
cloud-based tools that allow

00:10:31.920 --> 00:10:36.440
retailers to create customized
loyalty programs and targeted

00:10:36.440 --> 00:10:41.110
offers campaigns and really get
a great set of analytics

00:10:41.110 --> 00:10:43.700
that they can have access to
to know who their customers

00:10:43.700 --> 00:10:48.970
are, how they're shopping at
their locations, and whether

00:10:48.970 --> 00:10:52.790
the campaigns are effective in
terms of bringing users back

00:10:52.790 --> 00:10:56.210
into their stores and increasing
the basket size of

00:10:56.210 --> 00:10:57.230
their purchases.

00:10:57.230 --> 00:11:01.800
So one of the things that we're
trying to do is really

00:11:01.800 --> 00:11:05.510
make it easy not only for the
large retailer to use these

00:11:05.510 --> 00:11:09.160
tools for offers and loyalty
programs, but we want to make

00:11:09.160 --> 00:11:11.700
it accessible to small to
midsize retailers as well.

00:11:11.700 --> 00:11:14.030
And so over the next little
while, you're going to see

00:11:14.030 --> 00:11:18.170
Google Wallet create these new
cloud-based services that will

00:11:18.170 --> 00:11:22.790
make couponing campaigns,
loyalty campaigns accessible

00:11:22.790 --> 00:11:24.000
to all merchants.

00:11:24.000 --> 00:11:27.980
PENG YING: So it seems like you
are trying to tie online

00:11:27.980 --> 00:11:31.190
traffic with brick-and-mortar
store traffic, right?

00:11:31.190 --> 00:11:32.635
That's the goal?

00:11:32.635 --> 00:11:32.920
One of the goals.

00:11:32.920 --> 00:11:34.080
ROBIN DUA: That's one
of the goals.

00:11:34.080 --> 00:11:34.760
PENG YING: One of the goals.

00:11:34.760 --> 00:11:37.400
ROBIN DUA: And if you look at
what we're trying to do

00:11:37.400 --> 00:11:40.630
through the Wallet from a
consumer perspective, which is

00:11:40.630 --> 00:11:44.110
helping them discover great
offers that they're interested

00:11:44.110 --> 00:11:48.060
in and helping them connect with
merchants that they love.

00:11:48.060 --> 00:11:51.430
On the merchant side, we're also
trying to make it easier

00:11:51.430 --> 00:11:56.430
for them to connect with the
consumers that are shopping in

00:11:56.430 --> 00:11:59.270
their stores and help them bring
those consumers back

00:11:59.270 --> 00:12:00.860
into their stores.

00:12:00.860 --> 00:12:03.150
PENG YING: Seems really useful
to be able to say, hey, why

00:12:03.150 --> 00:12:05.690
don't you come back some time?

00:12:05.690 --> 00:12:09.080
So now that we talked about
that a little bit, can you

00:12:09.080 --> 00:12:13.970
kind of expand on the vision
of what we hope the Wallet

00:12:13.970 --> 00:12:14.970
ecosystem will be?

00:12:14.970 --> 00:12:18.520
What we hope to enable both
users of Wallet and any

00:12:18.520 --> 00:12:20.580
additional features and
functionality for merchants of

00:12:20.580 --> 00:12:22.320
Wallet to be able to offer?

